	  <title>Exercises: New Continuous Functions from Old</title>
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>Explain why the functions below are continuous.</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>f\from \RNr \to \RNr</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>f(x) = 3x^4 -x^2 + 1</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The function <math>
                           <latex>f</latex>
                        </math> is a polynomial (its degree is <math>
                           <latex>4</latex>
                        </math>). So it is continuous.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>g\from \RNr\to \RNr</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>g(x) = -2x^6 + 3x - 4</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>h\from \RNr\to \RNr</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>h(x) = e^2 \cdot t^9 - \pi\cdot t^6 + (\pi^2-e)\cdot t^3 + t - 6</latex>
                     </math>
                  </para.body>
               </para>
			         </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>The function <math>
                           <latex>h</latex>
                        </math> is a polynomial (its degree is <math>
                           <latex>9</latex>
                        </math>). So it is continuous. (No need to worry about problems arising from the coefficients <math>
                           <latex>e^2</latex>
                        </math>, <math>
                           <latex>\pi</latex>
                        </math>, <math>
                           <latex>(\pi^2-e)</latex>
                        </math>. These are just numbers. So we are, indeed, dealing with a polynomial.)</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
	
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
